06857nam a22009375i 9783110751963DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021951243  a97831107519637 a10.1515/97831107519632doi  a(DE-B1597)583515  a(OCoLC)1322125743  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041902bisacsh00aRethinking Orality II :bThe Mechanisms of the Oral Communication System in the Case of the Archaic Epos /ced. by Andrea Ercolani, Laura Lulli. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (X, 218 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTranscodification: Arts, Languages and Media ,x2702-7732 ;v200tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction: Orality and Epic Poetry. Old Questions and New Perspectives -- tMind-based Research Meets the Homeric Epics: Looking Again at Communicative Strategies in the Homeric Epics -- tInterformulaic Homer: Evidence from the "Wild" Papyri -- tTwo Chronological Extremes of the Homeric Language: πρόφρασσα and εἶπα -- tTechnologies of Orality: Formularity, Meter, and Kunstsprache in Homer -- tA Cyclic Theme in the Odyssey: The Oresteia in Zeus' Speech (1, 28-43) -- tAudiences of the Prophecy of Tiresias in Odyssey Book XI -- tTraces of Orality in the Histories: The Homeric 'Heritage' in Herodotean Battles and Speeches -- tSome Reflections on Orality and Epic Poetry in Ancient Literary Criticism -- tHomer and 'the Elegists': an Ancient Construction of Difference -- tParadoxes of 'Orality': A Comparison between Homeric Oral Poetry and the Heroic and Courtly Epics in Middle High German -- tEpos and Orality: Conclusive Remarks and Open Questions -- tIndex Notable Things -- tIndex Discussed Passages0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis is the second volume on the mechanisms of oral communication in ancient Greece, focused on epic poetry, a genre with deep roots in orality. Considering the critical debate about orality and its influence on the composition, diffusion and transmission of the archaic epic poems, the survey provides a reconsideration and a reassessment of the traces of orality in the archaic epic poetry, following their adaptation in the synchronic and diachronic changes of the communicative system. Combining the methods of cognitive science, and the historical and literary analysis of the texts, the research explores the complexity of the literary message of the Greek epic poetry, highlighting its position in a system of oral communication. The consideration of structural and formal aspects, i.e. the traces of orality in the narrative architecture, in the epic diction, in the meter and the formulaic system, as well as the vestiges of the mixture of orality and writing, allows to reconstruct a dynamic frame of communicative modalities which influenced and enriched the archaic epic poetry, providing it with expressive potentialities destined to a longlasting permanence in the history of the genre.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aAntiks Epos. 4aEpos / Antike. 4aHomer. 4aKommunikationssystem. 4aMündlichkeit. 4aTrankodierung. 4aTranscodierung. 4aTranslationswissenschaft. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aTranscodification.  aTranslation Studies.  aancient communicative system.  aarchaic Greek epic poetry.  aculture.  aorality.1 aBakker, Egbert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBozzone, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators